 size=1> Encounter in the Commonlands<br>
<br>
A starry night descends upon the western Commonlands as Eias prepares to camp for the evening. The howling of werewolves had ceased, their invasion thrown back to the desert from which they came. He had slain many, and was weary from the fight, but because of his effort and that of many other courageous souls, the Commonlands once again sleeps in peace.<br>
<br>
Hovering in a countenance of death, he meditates, reflecting on deep truths that few understand and even fewer know. A skeletal companion stands over him, keeping the fire warm and the perimeter safe. Eias is known by many in this part of Norrath as a power not to be trivialized, but there are still a few who would have the courage to attack him in this slightly vulnerable state. His protector's hollow eyes keep watch. A low fog begins to form on the ground as the air begins to cool. It is nothing unusual for this time of year. Eias finds it comforting, something akin to an evening back home. The companion continues its scans, and its eyes lock onto something approaching in the mist.<br>
<br>
A battered and exhausted young Teir'Dal comes stumbling into the camp. Barely lucid, she eyes Eias with distorted vision, only faintly seeing the hovering green-robed gentleman and his skeletal companions as she falls to her knees, unable to continue. Falling unconscious, her last vision is of Eias looking down upon her, the faint violet glow of his eyes adding to her fear. She is alive, but barely. Her shredded clothing barely functions to keep her modesty and they fail utterly to provide any kind of warmth in this cool night air. The young woman's feet are shackled, but the chain that would prevent flight is shattered. Cuts and bruises cover her dark indigo skin and some are bleeding badly. Placing his hand upon her chest, Eias channels a small bit of his life energy into her. Her open wounds stop bleeding and most of her bruises become smaller. He commands his companion to remove the shackles, whereupon it's powerful, bony hands rip them apart as if they were made of paper.<br>
<br>
The companion again locks his gaze in the direction from which the dark elf had come. &quot;She has pursuers, master!&quot; Carefully making their way through the mist and brush, three orcs of the Deathfist clan approach the camp, following the trail of blood left by the woman. The leader, a legionnaire, stops the two centurions with him and points toward the camp; they have noticed Eias and his skeletal sentry.<br>
<br>
&quot;We have no quarrel with you, Necromancer,&quot; shouts the legionnaire, &quot;but the woman comes with us!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I disagree,&quot; he replies with a very dark, threatening tone. He had just saved her life and was not about to let them take it from her.<br>
<br>
&quot;Your mistake. Centurions, attack!&quot;<br>
<br>
The centurions draw their blades and charge. Eias's companion promptly intercepts one, drawing two blades and engaging in a blinding dance of steel with the now outmatched orc. The legionnaire begins to close on the camp cautiously, looking for an opportunity to strike. The one charging Eias promptly finds its mind touched in the darkest reach. Fear begins to overwhelm him and he turns to run. His skin promptly withers as Eias rips the life force from him, adding it to his own and reducing the orc to a hollow husk of a corpse.<br>
<br>
The dance of steel between the Eias's skeletal protector and the other centurion ends abruptly when one of the skeleton's blades finds the orc's neck. The legionnaire suddenly discovers that he is the new dance partner and tries to bow out, backing away and fighting to keep the skeleton's blades away from his own neck. Knowing the attempt to be futile, he turns to run, whereupon two blades make a clean v-notch where his neck once rested.<br>
<br>
The brief battle ended, Eias decides it best to move camp. The trail of blood could bring more trouble and the scent of dead orc will only make it worse; the Commonlands are known for their large cougars and lions, not to mention grizzly bears. The companion could easily deal with such intrusions, but Eias is eager to minimize any danger to the young woman that he now protects. They move camp into a deeper thicket of brush and trees further away from any trails.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#003366><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub18.ezboard.com/beverquestroleplay49450.showUserPublicProfile?gid=thuud>thuud</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Player</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#778899>(11/2/02 2:48:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub18.ezboard.com/feverquestroleplay49450frm43.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.zoomnet.net/~russcm/everquest/characters/eias/graphics/photo.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Part 2</span><hr size=1> A Desperate Request<br>
<br>
Eias's young ward sleeps through the day. She appears to need much time to heal, only the channeling of life from him had kept her alive. Come the sunset, she stirs a bit and slowly opens her eyes. Her many wounds make moving difficult, but she manages to make note of her situation - safe and warm in a stranger's camp. She accepts a refreshing drink of water from her protector.<br>
<br>
&quot;Are you hungry,&quot; he inquires. Small bits of meat are warming over the campfire. Not the usual dried flesh you find sold by supply stores, but fresher kinds, as if he himself had hunted them. The scent of warm spice awakens her appetite. &quot;Yes, thank you,&quot; she weakly replies as she takes the small tin plate offered her. He serves up the meat with a bit of sweetened tea.<br>
<br>
&quot;Whom has fear brought to my camp,&quot; he asks.<br>
<br>
The tea and fresh meat has already strengthened her. &quot;I am Na`Tiel, of the family Vex.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Eias Rham,&quot; he introduces himself. &quot;Was it the orcs who harmed you?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No,&quot; she begins, &quot;I was on Kunark. A group of us were exploring a region to the east of my people's outpost there when we were set upon by Iksar. If I may ask, what is the date?&quot; Thinking for a moment, he states the date by the Teir`Dal calendar. &quot;Has it been that long, six months almost? The Iksar put us to work in a mine and kept us half starved so we could not regain our strength and use any magic. My sister was captured with me. She gave me her ration one day, which helped me get my strength up enough to fight off the guard on us and allow me to teleport myself to the spires south of here. I was trying to get to Neriak, but already weakened and wounded, I only got as far as here. I knew the orcs were pursuing me, but they had not yet found me.&quot; He offers her another helping of meat, which she gladly accepts. Even if she had not been half starved for the last six months, she would consider this meal exceptional. It seems that this traveler had decided to live well wherever he was. <br>
<br>
&quot;Neriak is not far from here,&quot; he notes, &quot;and I have a welcome reputation there. I will go with you to make sure you arrive.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I would appreciate that, but I would ask one other thing,&quot; she was recalling the air of power she felt from him as she collapsed helpless the previous night. &quot;Would you help me rescue my sister?&quot;<br>
<br>
He ponders for a long moment. &quot;Let me get you to Neriak first,&quot; he replies. Many confusing and conflicting thoughts made it difficult for him to commit at this point.<br>
<br>
&quot;I do not wish to sound like I am begging, but if it's an issue of reward, I can show you where they keep the gems and mithril ore they were mining.&quot; She was recalling hearing his name spoken in circles of power in Neriak, and was desperately trying to think of ways to get his help, even considering offering herself to him.<br>
<br>
&quot;It is not an issue of reward or anything like that,&quot; he states, smiling slightly. &quot;Do not mistake my living well here as a sign of wealth or a desire for comfort, as this comfort is more to do with frugality than finance. Besides, if I know the Iksar as I do, it will take more than the two of us to accomplish a rescue.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Actually,&quot; she notes, &quot;there weren't many guards at the mine. It was high in the mountains where few people traveled. Most of the guard was committed to escorting the material back to their city. I know the remnant would be no match for you.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Either way, it is best to get you back to Neriak first. Your people should know what happened, maybe they will be able to help as well.&quot; He is beginning to truly understand how close she and her sister must be if she is so willing to set out now to try to rescue her. Going to Neriak would not add much length to a journey to Kunark either way. Resigning herself to the facts, she agrees, and at sunrise they set off for the Teir`Dal city.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#336699><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub18.ezboard.com/beverquestroleplay49450.showUserPublicProfile?gid=thuud>thuud</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Player</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#778899>(11/2/02 8:17:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub18.ezboard.com/feverquestroleplay49450frm43.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.zoomnet.net/~russcm/everquest/characters/eias/graphics/photo.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Part 3</span><hr size=1> Dark Empathies and Understandings<br>
<br>
They arrive in Neriak a few days after departing their camp in the Commonlands, having traveled slowly, Na`Tiel's wounds still giving her trouble. Eias does his best to minimize her discomfort, but she has been badly abused by the Iksar. Her former captors are known for their cruelty, but Eias had not previously heard of them being bold enough to take Teir`Dal as slaves, frogloks being their preferred choice. He ponders this change and what it may mean.<br>
<br>
Stories had filtered back to him concerning disappearances of former companions he had known when he journeyed to Kunark. Adventuring as he does makes few lasting friendships, as many who follow this lifestyle are in it for the reward of material and power; some for self, some others less selfishly for their societies. Eias journeys seeking both goals, with the ultimate goal of bringing respect to both his home and himself. Such is the dilemma before him now. If the Iksar have captured former companions of his, he could free them and bring respect to himself. However, if he did so, then he may provoke their captors who, as he does, also follow Cazic Thule. The people of Paineel, his home, are by default grouped among the rest as outsiders by the Iksar and as such dealt with as invaders, but still there is hope that someday Calibis and Paineel could be allied. Though friendly toward Paineel, the Teir`Dal have no such problem battling the Iksar, as they follow their creator, Innoruuk.<br>
<br>
&quot;What troubles you,&quot; questions a voice that wakes Eias from his thoughts. Na`Tiel has returned. They had gone to the temple of Innoruuk to see to her injuries where he was waiting outside on a balcony overlooking the caverns. Now healed and clad in a deep black robe with runes denoting her as a wizard, her true beauty is evident, her ebon hair braided in a way that reminds Eias of woven midnight.<br>
<br>
&quot;You are looking well,&quot; he notes, attempting to evade answering her. Even wounded, she had been lovely, but he is still surprised.<br>
<br>
She could tell from his expression that he found her beautiful. Pleasantly flattered that such a one of power would lower his guard enough to show such admiration toward her, she replies, &quot;Thank you.&quot; Not one to let him slip by that easily, she continues, &quot;That does not answer the question, though.&quot;<br>
<br>
Knowing she will not relent, he requests, &quot;ask me again later.&quot;<br>
<br>
She did not like that answer. The thought of not having him along to rescue her sister was devastating. It is well known that one should not force someone of his power to walk where he did not wish to walk, but she was still determined to at least try. &quot;Why later? I know I owe you my life and you owe me nothing, but I have to ask this. Do you intend to leave now?&quot;<br>
<br>
Smiling gently to calm her, he reassures, &quot;No, I simply do not know how to tell you of my concern.&quot; He walks with her back into the temple area, where two members of the wizard's guild meet them. They have come to escort her to the guild leaders.<br>
<br>
He waits for her at an inn in the foreign quarter, still pondering his choices. Going with her at least to the Outpost will do no harm except to make it more difficult if he decided not to proceed to the mine. Although never personally loosing someone such a family member, he could relate how painful it would be to loose one so close. Nothing was forcing him to go, but for some reason he was starting to believe he needed to. Was this part of the dark road required of him?<br>
<br>
&quot;Something heavy weighs on your brow, I see,&quot; notes a voice from behind Eias. A dark robed Teir`Dal gentleman joins him at his table overlooking the town below. The runes upon his robe mark him as a leader of the Neriak wizards. &quot;I may be able to help.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Perhaps,&quot; Eias replies, &quot;but the decision is mine alone in the end.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I am not here to force the decision, but simply to add another side to the debate.&quot; Signaling the waiter for what appears to be his usual, the gentleman continues, &quot;you are respected by our order and the other orders of this great city. I come to request your assistance not only on behalf of Na`Tiel Vex, but on behalf of all the orders. You may not be considered an ally, but you are not an enemy. You are trustworthy and deserving of the respect given you by our leaders.<br>
<br>
&quot;You have been to the area of the Frontier Mountains she has described. It has been decided that action in the full name of the Teir`Dal be taken against these Lizard Men, these Iksar as they call themselves. You could make a valuable guide and with your help it would be almost guaranteed that anyone we send would arrive at the mine.&quot;<br>
<br>
The waiter brings the gentleman's beverage. He takes a sip, then nods to the waiter his acceptance of the drink, as if to judge it's quality before receipt. Continuing, he explains, &quot;We will send a dragoon to escort you to the Outpost. He will bring sealed orders to the Outpost's commander with detailed instructions as to what to do. You know our kind, Eias; we do not take action piecemeal. Once someone inspires our hate, we are focused. We are creatures of hate, and our combined hate makes us strong. All we need from you is an extra hand to make sure we can deliver that hate to the offenders.&quot;<br>
<br>
This seems to be the answer Eias is hoping to receive. He knew that by coming here the leaders of the city would want vengeance. &quot;I will come then. I will add my power to the fight.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Excellent. Na`Tiel and the dragoon will be here soon.&quot; The gentleman, having finished his drink, rises and offers his hand in traditional Teir`Dal fashion, which Eias takes firmly, as custom. &quot;Someday, when your people need us, you will be able to count on at least some of us, perhaps all. I have other rounds to make. Good journey, friend of Neriak.&quot;<br>
<br>
About an hour later, Eias notes a large procession of robed figures moving in the street below. Center to the crowd is Na`Tiel, accompanied by an aged woman bearing a crest of high rank and a gentleman in ceremonial warrior garments. The warrior, woman, and Na`Tiel make their way to Eias's table on the overlook, the remnant of the crowd gathering as if to bear witness to what was about to happen. The woman begins to address Eias, &quot;You are the one who has chosen to be guardian to Na`Tiel Vex?&quot;<br>
<br>
Standing, Eias replies, &quot;Yes, I am.&quot;<br>
<br>
The woman continues, &quot;You have saved her life once. That was not required of you then, nor is anything further required of you now. Some cultures profess that once you save a life, that life is yours to care for and protect. Neither the culture of the Erudites nor the culture of the Teir`Dal professes to such tradition. Additionally, only she can decide if she feels obligated to return any debt of gratitude toward you, we will not hold her to any, and neither may you.<br>
<br>
&quot;You have chosen to be guardian on the mission to rescue her younger sister from the bondage of the Iksar. Additionally, you will assist in the upcoming battle where you choose, but you will assist. If you do choose to accept this freely, know that leaving without completion of the mission will most likely invoke our enmity and be disallowed access to our city. Success in the mission, and you will have our gratitude, something that can be of value to you in the future.<br>
<br>
&quot;You have but one chance to reply, do you accept this task given you, Eias Rham of Paineel, freely?&quot;<br>
<br>
Without hesitation, he replies, &quot;Yes.&quot;<br>
<br>
An unmistakable smile appears on Na`Tiel's face. She is placing heavy hopes in Eias, something he is not use to dealing with. He has been a loner most of his life, having responsibility for another is something he has chosen to avoid. It is why he does not frequent Freeport as much as he did in the past, Sariah and Leirna must not feel dependent on him. Now he has Na`Tiel and a promise. He will do his best to honor both, all the while making attempts to bury his uneasiness.<br>
<br>
&quot;Na`Tiel Vex,&quot; the woman continues, turning toward her, &quot;do you accept Eias as your guardian in this endeavor.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes,&quot; she replies.<br>
<br>
Turning toward the gentleman in the warriors garb, the woman takes an amulet from him and hands it to Na`Tiel. &quot;Signify your acceptance by bestowing upon him the Rune of the Guardian.&quot;<br>
<br>
Taking it, Na`Tiel nervously brings it to Eias, her heart racing uncontrollably. Hesitating for a brief but uncomfortable moment, she beacons him to bow slightly, he being a good foot taller than any Teir`Dal. Smiling softly, he leans forward, withdrawing his hood, and she places the amulet around his neck.<br>
<br>
&quot;Upon receipt of this rune,&quot; the woman proceeds, &quot;your voice becomes our voice in matters concerning her safety. Where you speak, we speak. Those who hear you, hear us. You are but one of very few outsiders to whom we have given this power and responsibility. Do not think it trivial.&quot;<br>
<br>
Standing tall again and returning his hood to its place, he thanks the woman. Taking Na`Tiel by the hand, he vows, &quot;I shall not fail in this.&quot;<br>
<br>
Bowing, the woman concludes, &quot;may Innoruuk and Cazic Thule bless this endeavor with their power.&quot; She turns to depart, as does the crowd that came with them. The warrior moves forward to join Eias and Na`Tiel.<br>
<br>
Still holding her hand, Eias shows Na`Tiel to a chair at his table. &quot;Sadly, I have to wish the blessing be not quite what she hopes,&quot; he says softly as he sits.<br>
<br>
Puzzled, Na`Tiel inquires, &quot;is that part of what you are going to explain when I ask later, I hope?&quot; Nodding slightly, he looks up to greet the warrior joining them.<br>
<br>
&quot;Guardian, I am Dragoon Til`Vahn of the Indigo Brotherhood. I have been assigned to help you.&quot; He holds out his hand in the traditional Teir`Dal manor.<br>
<br>
Eias takes his hand firmly. &quot;Pleased to meet you. Join us if you will.&quot;<br>
<br>
Til`Vahn sits, and they discuss the upcoming journey. &quot;Several others have been dispatched to gather assistance for the battle, &quot;he begins,  &quot;but we are to go directly to the Outpost. I estimate we can be there in eight days if we leave at sunrise and have no delays.&quot; <br>
<br>
They complete the plans for the journey, Til`Vahn departs to make some final arrangements. Looking down from the balcony, Na`Tiel makes note of the pleasant view. &quot;I have always liked it,&quot; Eias states, &quot;its relaxing. However, it is time for me to sleep.&quot;<br>
<br>
They rise from the table, Na`Tiel taking one last look of the view. &quot;You're still not ready to tell me, are you,&quot; she asks.<br>
<br>
Pausing uncomfortably, he replies, &quot;no.&quot;<br>
<br>
Thinly disguising her disappointment with humor, she asks, &quot;So, guardian, where shall I stay tonight.&quot;<br>
<br>
Pleasantly amused, he replies, &quot;you should be safe enough at home.&quot; He turns to head to the main desk of the inn.<br>
<br>
She takes him by the arm, stopping him. &quot;Wait,&quot; she asks. After a brief pause, she continues, &quot;stay with me tonight. The house will be empty without Na`Vaar there. Besides, I may need you when I get there, I have not yet been home.&quot;<br>
<br>
Seeing her fear clearly, he agrees.<br>
