<br>
Til`Vahn had arrived ahead of Na`Tiel and Eias at the gate. The guards there know him well, and are bidding him farewell. Well - wishings are shared all around as they prepare to depart, although Eias can tell some of the guard is uncomfortable with an outsider being guardian to such a one as Na`Tiel. He can do nothing to change that, this path chose him as much as he chose it.<br>
<br>
Departing Neriak, the three proceed south into the Nektulous forest toward the valley that leads to the eastern Commonlands. A river bridge along the path marks the last protection the Indigo Brotherhood's guards would provide until they reached the Outpost. Perpetual undeclared wars between raiders, orcs, and the Teir`Dal rage in the hills and forest south of the river and into the Commonlands, where the Freeport Militia holds power. The band, however, will receive little help this time from the Militia.<br>
<br>
Exiting the valley to the Commonlands, they pause to rest. It is nearing late afternoon. Their plan is to proceed across at sunset, arriving in the guards patrol area after dark. The Militia's reaction to dark elves is mixed; one never knows if they will kill or ignore. Eias is known to the militia; alone he would be ignored. This time, however, as guardian to a Teir`Dal wizard, he does not wish to be seen.<br>
<br>
Eias prepares an evening meal of his usual fine quality. Til`Vahn, not being accustomed to eating so well in the field, is quite pleased; he thanks Innoruuk for his fortune. The scent of spiced meat does attract the occasional large cat, but they are persuaded to leave. The sun begins to set over the mountains in the distance, and they pack to proceed. While admiring one last view, Na`Tiel eyes Eias whispering something to a shadowy shape, which departs quickly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Who was that,&quot; she inquires.<br>
<br>
&quot;A messenger with a message for some friends,&quot; he explains. &quot;If they get the message, you will meet them.&quot;<br>
<br>
Untold centuries ago, when the desert dunes began encroaching on the fertile lands here, a forgotten people built a tunnel through the hills in an attempt to preserve a passage to the Lake of Marr and points south. The tunnel still exists, and the desert came, drying out the southern area of the Commonlands and forming the northern reaches of the desert of Ro, the lake now being referred to as the Oasis of Marr. The three begin to approach the tunnel, travelling unseen and avoiding the militia.<br>
<br>
&quot;We should rest at the tunnel, near the entrance,&quot; Eias notes. &quot;If my friends received the message, they will meet us there.&quot;<br>
<br>
Til`Vahn is uneasy with the idea of meeting up with anyone. &quot;Are these friends of yours tolerant?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;They tolerate me after a fashion,&quot; he replies, a bit of dark humor implied.<br>
<br>
&quot;After a fashion, that is still not comforting,&quot; Til`Vahn remarks.<br>
<br>
They make camp a ways into the entrance of the tunnel. They will proceed through at sunrise and then through the desert that lies beyond the next night. The usual evening fog of the Commonlands was forming, the tunnel's already cooler air making the fog deeper where they camp.<br>
<br>
Little is being said between the three, they are all fatigued. Eias begins a meditative exercise to restore his energies in case it is needed there. Moonlight was filling the entrance to the tunnel, and outlined in the fog two cloaked figures began to approach the camp.<br>
<br>
A young woman's voice calls out from the fog, inquiring, &quot;is their room by that fire for friends?&quot;<br>
<br>
Motioning the others to be silent, Eias answers, &quot;of course. I hope my dark messenger found you well.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;He did,&quot; comes the reply, &quot;but he startled me in the midst of meditation.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Indeed. I shall have to speak with him about his timing then,&quot; he notes, standing to greet his two friends with the warmest of embraces. He introduces the one who spoke as Sariah, a white - cloaked golden haired woman bearing a gold and ivory guilded sword and markings that shows her to be a paladin of Erollisi. The one with her he introduces as her younger sister, Leirna, a well dressed dark haired youth that seems to show the greater affection for Eias.<br>
<br>
Uneasily, Til`Vahn greets the newcomers. Keeping one eye on Sariah, he makes room for the sisters to sit. Na`Tiel seems a bit more at ease, trusting that these friends of Eias are no threat. Leirna produces several bundles of fresh fish and vegetables, making note of how she has missed Eias's cooking. Things begin to relax more as he gives each a task in preparing the meal.<br>
<br>
Sariah begins relating some events that have transpired since Eias's last visit to Freeport. &quot;It is good that you have come now. You know of Braxen Kurn, of course,&quot; she begins, &quot;He has not relented, in fact, he is stepping up his hunt for you. I overheard him speaking to a gentleman, an Erudite, at the temple recently. I believe his name was Palatos or something similar.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Palatos Kynarn,&quot; Eias inquires.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, I believe so,&quot; she confirms. &quot;Do you know him?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I am familiar with him,&quot; he notes, &quot;He is one of the Craftkeepers, part of the High Council of Erudin. They have hunted my people for generations simply to silence us. They spread more fear about us than we spread fear in general.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Apparently he is now helping Braxen,&quot; she continues, &quot;and the plan is to ruin your reputation in Freeport. Braxen went on to Velious, apparently on his way to Thurgadin to do the same there. One by one he plans on poisoning people to turn on you and your people.&quot;<br>
<br>
Eias seems disturbed by this. &quot;Palatos should know better, he is far away from home and alone in Freeport. He should not be giving me a reason to confront him. Odds are if I do, he will immediately cry for guards and start a fight, forcing me to kill him.&quot;<br>
<br>
Sariah knows that is likely exactly what will happen, and it's the confrontation Braxen wants as proof of Eias's menace. &quot;Should I speak up for you, confront him instead?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No,&quot; he replies quickly, &quot;that would just make trouble for you, and you have already risked enough for me. I will have to deal with this eventually.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Who is this Braxen,&quot; interrupts Na`Tiel, &quot;and why is he after you?&quot;<br>
<br>
The fish are cooking and the vegetables stewing. As they cook, Eias relates the story of how he fought a companion of Braxen, a Sir Edwin Motte of the Knights of Truth. Edwin had murdered a fellow's student, and in exchange for some assistance given to Eias, he had vowed to avenge the act. After the fight, Braxen confronted the Knights, and the only reason Eias was not a hunted man in their eyes is the fact that Sariah had spoken on his behalf. She had noted that Eias had done nothing different than what Edwin would have done if the roles were reversed.<br>
<br>
Til`Vahn finds something of irony in the last part of the tale. &quot;Interesting that a paladin of Erollisi would be so bold as to question truths brought before the Knights of Truth, followers of Erollisi's brother Mithaniel.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Not really,&quot; Sariah notes, &quot;at times my role is simply one who speaks truths from another point of view.&quot;<br>
<br>
The meal is ready. Feigning a bit of a chill, Leirna moves closer to Eias while she eats; the hot tea and fish are quite warming. Na`Tiel inquires as to how Eias had met the sisters.<br>
<br>
&quot;That in itself is quite a story as well,&quot; Sariah begins. She tells of how she was guarding a caravan heading from Freeport to a villa in the oasis. They were ambushed by a band of orcs who held a grudge against the caravan leaders. &quot;In the midst of the fight, I became the last one standing in the area where I was. I quickly ended up on the ground, and bleeding, basically finished. An orc was over me with a blade resting on my heart.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;It's wasn't as bad as you makes it sound,&quot; Eias interjects. &quot;At that point it was at least three to one, and you had already taken out two.&quot; Til`Vahn appears impressed by that fact, while Leirna is uncomfortable listening to it totally.<br>
<br>
&quot;Well, true,&quot; she continues, smiling humbly. &quot;As the orc raised its blade to finish me, it suddenly staggers. The life drains out of its eyes and it dries up like a raisin. It slumps to the ground at my feet. I manage to crawl away from it slightly, and see this fellow with a skeleton following him. I had never seen or met a Necromancer until then, so all I knew of them is their reputation for being someone who would kill you rather than look at you. I thought I was about to die by his hands. As I passed out from my wounds, I saw him reach down for me. All I remember after that is a warm sensation coming over me, then waking up in his camp.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I can relate to that experience,&quot; Na`Tiel notes. Smiling, she relates her first encounter with Eias. &quot;It seems that mercy sometimes comes when you least expect it.&quot;<br>
<br>
The otherwise quiet Leirna speaks up to that. &quot;Mercy that saves your family.&quot; She has finished eating and was now leaning against Eias, his arm around her.<br>
<br>
Na`Tiel notes an irony, and relates how they are on a mission to rescue her sister. She was beginning to feel a kinship with these humans, something she did not expect. Humans and Teir`Dal are not ones to trust one another unless there are reasons to change the mistrust. She was finding such a reason here. &quot;I wish,&quot; she states, &quot;that their had been such mercy when my parents were lost in the battle at Kithicor.&quot; They have all heard the stories of that bloody day, and all know the horror that place now holds for anyone who passes through.<br>
<br>
Til`Vahn is starting to ease his wariness of Sariah. He is beginning to respect her as a fellow warrior, although he would have no problem slaying her on a field of battle. Until that happened, though, he would not hesitate to fight at her side.<br>
<br>
They continue speaking through the night. The time draws late and the sky outside begins to lighten a bit. The time has come for the three to move on. Sariah and Leirna bid warm farewells to Eias and his companions, Leirna holding her embrace of him a bit long. As they parted company, Na`Tiel makes note of how quiet Leirna seemed to be.<br>
<br>
&quot;There was little to say,&quot; he notes with a touch of sorrow in his voice. &quot;Most was said long ago, and the rest needs no words.&quot;<br>
