<br>
The band's journey through the tunnel and into the desert is uneventful, the combined power of Na`Tiel and Eias makes traveling unseen quite easy. Coming onto a set of dunes just north of the ancient lake known as the Oasis of Marr, they spy a group of anxious men huddled in a make - shift hiding place. Curious as to the reason, Eias has his companions wait for him while he investigates.<br>
<br>
&quot;It has to be an inky invasion,&quot; Eias hears as he approaches, &quot;why else would they be here in such number?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;They haven't moved much off the beach,&quot; another notes, &quot;either way you know the darkies are up to no good. That fleet of theirs off the coast may mean to carry them up to Freeport.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;There's only three ships though,&quot; notes one who seems to be calmer than the rest, &quot;that wouldn't be enough to take Freeport.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Not alone,&quot; replies the second, &quot;but definitely enough to take the harbor! Come on then, we have to warn the militia!&quot;<br>
<br>
Failing miserably to be stealthy, the group of men scampers north heading for the city. Eias returns to his group, relaying what he saw. &quot;Do you recall them mentioning anything about ships,&quot; he inquires of Til`Vahn.<br>
<br>
&quot;No,&quot; he replies, &quot;but I was not told the entire plan either, and I was under the impression that they were still gathering resources as we left.&quot;<br>
<br>
They move on, over the last few dunes to the Oasis. As they approach the seacoast near the lake, Eias notes a trio of masts prominently set against the sunrise. Reaching the summit of a nearby rocky hill, he looks down upon an armed camp assembled around the small docks used by travelers to the Timorous Deep and beyond. The three masts belong to a large vessel anchored offshore, who herself is flanked by two smaller single - mast ships. All three appear to be ships of war! Eias can make out at least a full platoon of Teir`Dal marines garrisoning the area around the docks.<br>
<br>
This seemed out of place to him. To the Teir`Dal, the art of Wizardry is considered a second class endeavor; even the Wizards guild refers to itself as the Spurned. Why all this effort to simply rescue the sister of an otherwise unimportant wizard and punish her abductors? Was it worth it to risk three precious warships from their small fleet to transport her and whoever else comes? This was clearly not an invasion, the Oasis of Marr is not strategic enough to capture and there was clearly no plan in the works or no indication in Neriak of any attack pending on Freeport.<br>
<br>
Approaching the camp, Eias places the guardian rune in plain site. The three are greeted by a patrol of marines and shown to a tent. &quot;Greetings, Guardian,&quot; shouts a voice from within the crowded tent. Making his way through the assembled, the commander of the marines greets the three warmly. Central to the tent, a gentleman is briefing the crowd on the timetable of the fleet. He makes note of how for reasons of expedience these ships were sent to bring them more quickly to the Outpost; the usual transports run by the Ogres being too slow. Concluding his briefing, the gentleman, whom Eias determines is the second in command of the main vessel, states the fleet will sail with the sunrise, using the offshore morning breeze to speed them into the Deep. The crowd then disperses. The marine commander takes Til`Vahn aside to discuss something, while Eias and Na`Tiel mill about the camp. <br>
<br>
Overwhelmed by the scale of things, Na`Tiel is puzzled. She was told even less about the plans that Til`Vahn. Coming to the dock, they eye a marine lieutenant arguing with an ogre, apparently operator of one of the transport rafts which carry passengers to his island in the Deep. Na`Tiel translates part of the debate to Eias; the ogre is protesting his loss of business, while the lieutenant explains the situation as temporary and vital to the needs of Neriak.<br>
<br>
Til`Vahn returns with several others. &quot;We are to be taken aboard in about a half hour with this group,&quot; he explains, introducing them as a troop of scouts from the Ebon Mask guild. Na`Tiel smiles as the scout's leader introduces himself as Vaxn Texxnev.<br>
<br>
&quot;Good to see you again, cousin,&quot; she says warmly.<br>
<br>
&quot;And you, Na`Tiel,&quot; he replies. &quot;When I heard Na`Vaar was among those taken, I had to come.&quot;<br>
<br>
They gather their gear at the docks and wait for the boats to return to take them to the ships. One of the scouts has a spyglass, and Eias asks if he can borrow it. Scanning the ships, he notes their names. The largest and apparently the flagship bears the proud name 'Innoruuk's Rage', perhaps a name meant to convey her power. She is large, well armed, and looks to be a match for anything the humans or gnomes have put to see. Eias had not before seen any Teir`Dal ships of this size, which may mean she is unique - another sign that there is more afoot than a simple rescue. The other, slightly smaller vessels bear equally grand names, 'Night of Bloody Kithicor' and 'Hate's Flame'.<br>
<br>
While panning between the ships, he spots the outline of another vessel on the horizon. Adjusting the spyglass a bit to improve focus, he looks again. It appears at first to be a two - mast fast merchant, a typical vessel that travels out of Freeport to points all over the Ocean of Tears and Timorous Deep. Looking closer, however, he notes it is flying the flag of Erudin and the command pennant is that of a Knight of Prexus. Rare indeed its it to see an Erudite vessel in these waters. Bearing out coincidence, Eias draws out a conclusion, Braxen Kurn had acquired his own ship, nothing unusual for a follower of the Ocean Lord.<br>
<br>
Noting his focus on something distant, Na`Tiel inquires, &quot;what is it?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Between the 'Rage' and the 'Kithicor' on the horizon,&quot; he notes as he hands here the glass. Spotting the ship, she draws the same conclusion as he. The 'Rage' had also spotted the merchant, and one of the lookouts was keeping an eye on her from the mainmast.<br>
<br>
&quot;You think we should do something about him now,&quot; she inquires as the longboats arrive to take them to the ships.<br>
<br>
&quot;Likely not,&quot; Eias concludes. &quot;Sariah said he was heading to Velious, probably on his way to Thurgadin. If that is the case, he has two things going against him right away. I have fought the Dain's enemies side by side with his forces, and that ship of his will not last long in the Iceclad Ocean. The Dain may receive him and listen, but will likely do nothing, and the ship will become a burden, probably sinking before he can use it to go elsewhere. No big loss, as he likely will be able to acquire alternate means of leaving Velious.&quot;<br>
<br>
Braxen is reviewing charts in the captain's cabin with his navigator and the gnomish mercenary they have contracted to assist in their transit of the ice around the only open port in Velious. One of the crew enters. &quot;My Lord, your Lieutenant has spotted something you should see.&quot; Knowing Krajn would not summon him unless it was important, he comes up from below. Seeing the Teir`Dal fleet on the horizon, he inquires if they have been hailed.<br>
<br>
Krajn replies, &quot;no, but that's not what I wanted you to see.&quot; Handing him his spyglass, he notes, &quot;on the dock, the green robed Erudite.&quot;<br>
<br>
Peering though the glass, he spots the individual Krajn indicated. &quot;Eias,&quot; he exclaims through clenched teeth, &quot;what is he doing there? Alter course, take us in!&quot;<br>
<br>
The crew begins to comply. &quot;Those are warships, M'Lord,&quot; cautions Krajn, &quot;Teir`Dal warships.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I know what they are,&quot; Braxen states firmly, trying to hold in the rage he felt toward Eias. Pondering a moment, he commands, &quot;Signalman, send up a hail!&quot;<br>
<br>
Eias and his companions are brought aboard the 'Rage'. She is to act as transport for the journey to the Outpost. As they come aboard, he notices an archer in the bow fire a signal arrow seaward. He sees the ship he spotted on the horizon has turned shoreward, toward the fleet.<br>
<br>
&quot;Red signal arrow, M'Lord,&quot; Krajn notes, &quot;they are warning us away and they have not returned the hail.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Signalman,&quot; Braxen commands, &quot;send that we wish to send a party aboard or ashore, their choice, to confer with their commander! First officer, slow our approach!&quot;<br>
<br>
The 'Rage's' captain is forward with the archer. Seeing the hail and message, he directs his attention shoreward, ordering a signalman to send to someone by the camp. Eias watches the exchange as a crewman takes his belongings below to his cabin. Na`Tiel, curious as to what is transpiring, stays by Eias.<br>
<br>
&quot;The captain is communicating with his admiral ashore,&quot; he explains to her. &quot;He is inquiring as to whether or not he wants to meet with the captain of the merchant per his request. It appears not.&quot; <br>
<br>
The captain orders a flag - hoist, signaling the admiral's command to the other ships, which promptly begin raising anchor and setting sails.<br>
<br>
&quot;They have ordered escorts to intercept and keep us at distance,&quot; Krajn reports to Braxen as another red signal arrow is launched their way.<br>
<br>
Swearing a curse under his breath, Braxen orders the ship turned parallel to shore and headway reduced to minimal. &quot;Signal again,&quot; he shouts, &quot;this is Captain, 'Vengeance of Prexus' requesting face to face with commander of fleet!&quot;<br>
<br>
'Kithicor' and 'Flame' rig for full speed and head strait at the 'Prexus'. Knowing the Teir`Dal will not likely allow him to remain, Braxen relents. &quot;Accursed spawns of Innoruuk! You will perish along with the Heretics you harbor! Full sail, get us out of here and resume course!&quot; 'Flame' takes up a shadowing position on 'Prexus', while 'Kithicor' falls back, guarding against the chance of another intruder.<br>
<br>
Most of the crew and passengers of the 'Rage' are on deck to witness the chase, Eias of course the most curious. Na`Tiel makes note of one particular gentleman on the fantail, pointing him out to Eias. &quot;That is Varum Tolax.&quot; Recognizing the family name, Eias inquires if his relation to Nexxka Tolax, the guild leader of the Dead's shadow knight corps. &quot;His son,&quot; she notes.<br>
<br>
The chase of the 'Prexus' lasts about an hour and the escorts return to their anchorage. Eias and Na`Tiel retire to their cabin, they have been assigned the same one, Til`Vahn being assigned the neighboring cabin. Being close to midday now, a meal has been brought to them, a classic mariner's meal of cod and dried fruit. While not appealing to Na`Tiel, Eias finds it quite nostalgic. <br>
<br>
&quot;Erudites are by nature a people of the sea,&quot; Eias begins. &quot;Even though my people have been driven into the mountains, some of our children's tails are still stories of the sea.&quot;<br>
<br>
Sitting by a view - port facing the sea, she wonders, &quot;do you think Braxen knew you were here?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;He may have seen me on the dock,&quot; he notes, &quot;odds are he had a bigger spyglass than that one fellows.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;That would make sense,&quot; she replies as she gets more fruit, &quot;likely one of the few things around here that is making sense to you at the moment.&quot;<br>
<br>
Smiling, Eias remarks, &quot;you've noticed that, I see. I was wondering, who else was captured with you?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I thought you knew,&quot; she states, &quot;but seeing the look on your face when you saw 'Innoruuk's Rage' anchored here, I began to realize you didn't. We were lead by Kav D`Vinn and Neroxn Quexill&quot;<br>
<br>
Eias finally understood. &quot;Ambassador D'Vinn's nephew and Xon Quexill's niece! It's not a wonder they haven't called down Innoruuk himself on Calibis at this point!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;There's more,&quot; she notes. &quot;Na`Vaar had recently been the subject of not a few romantic approaches by one of Xon's sons. It stands to reason that you are being watched by the Dead to see if you can bring home someone who is potential kin to their guild - master. The only reason I am along is an excuse to get your cooperation. We are likely both pawns.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Nothing unusual in that when the Dead are concerned.&quot; Eias's prior dealings with that guild of Necromancers have shown them to be devious and cunning, but also rather cautious and manipulative.<br>
<br>
After their meal, Eias begins an afternoon meditation, focusing on the upcoming mission. He has been to sea several times, and finds the sound of the ocean quite relaxing and mind - clearing. Na`Tiel, believing the time right, takes this chance to ask Eias a question.<br>
<br>
&quot;Back at the temple,&quot; she begins, &quot;I asked what troubled you, and you said to ask later.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You are asking again,&quot; he replies.<br>
<br>
Smiling slightly, she states, &quot;Yes.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You said your sister had given you her ration,&quot; he notes, &quot;What do you think the Iksar do to the ones who help others escape?&quot;<br>
<br>
A heavy feeling suddenly hits Na`Tiel. She had not thought of that. Meekly, she replies, &quot;I don't know. Punish her I would assume.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Do you know what Iksar eat,&quot; he inquires.<br>
<br>
&quot;I have heard mainly meat.&quot; She does not want to hear what Eias is implying.<br>
<br>
Trying to phrase it as easily as he can yet still add bluntness to the statement, he informs, &quot;to them, everything not Iksar is meat, save that which is plant.&quot;<br>
<br>
Looking away, out to sea, she covers her eyes to hide the upwelling of tears. &quot;So you think she is dead? Is that why you did not want to come.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No, but it was part of my reasoning,&quot; he continues. He explains how both his people, the Erudite Heretics as he tells her Braxen's people call them, and the Iksar both follow the Lord of Fear, Cazic Thule. &quot;If I were to risk any sort of future between Paineel and Calibis on what may be a futile effort, I had to believe your sister was still alive or find some alternative goal to justify going. The only goal I could find was improving my standing in Neriak. Even if your sister were dead and buried, your priests could do something about that, although likely at a high price for someone. If, however, she were dead but not buried, we have again futility.&quot;<br>
<br>
Na`Tiel is now feeling the full weight of what Eias is saying. Na`Vaar may have paid more of a price than either could have imagined when she gave up her ration. Weeping softly, she feels Eias's hands on her shoulders. He had shown her the fear that she had ignored, as is his way. She now turns that fear into hate, which is her way. &quot;If she is gone,&quot; she says, voice still trembling, &quot;then I vow to Innoruuk I will see them all destroyed!&quot;<br>
