<br>
The early evening sky lights occasionally as some distant storm releases its energy into the sea, spawning the wind that carries the fleet to its destination. Come nightfall the next evening, save anything unseen, they should be moored at the Outpost of the Teir`Dal in Kunark. Varum Tolax stands mid ship, watching the distant maelstrom, dismayed.<br>
<br>
&quot;This is no place for a warrior,&quot; he comments as Eias and Na`Tiel stroll by. &quot;The only battles out here are simple sports played between Karana and Prexus.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No stomach for the sea, Varum,&quot; inquires Na`Tiel, a bit of jaded humor being implied.<br>
<br>
&quot;No, none at all,&quot; he replies firmly, &quot;give me dry land and an army of my fellow knights. That is a warriors place.&quot;<br>
<br>
Eias and Na`Tiel join Varum in watching the storms. They seem to hint prophecy, for in less than a week they will be engaged in battle, as sky and sea are now. That battle, though, will not be for play, as seems to be happening between the Rainbringer and the Ocean Lord.<br>
<br>
&quot;Speaking of place,&quot; Varum continues after a moments pause, &quot;have you figured out yours yet, Guardian.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I have,&quot; Eias replies, &quot;I am sure the Dead had their reasons for not wanting to send a necromancer of their own.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Indeed,&quot; Varum states. &quot;The only reason I am here is because of concern for the leader's niece. Any concern for this one's sister is only token.&quot; Turning to go below, he adds, &quot;How does it feel to be sent on a fool's errand, Guardian.&quot;<br>
<br>
Na`Tiel becomes agitated, her hand searches for the knife at her side. &quot;Be silent, Varum,&quot; she commands through tight lips.<br>
<br>
Placing his hand on her shoulder in an attempt to calm her, Eias replies, &quot;a fools errand it is not, there are rewards to be had here.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh,&quot; Varum says, stopping. &quot;What sort of reward can come from rescuing someone who has likely already been turned to lizard offal and bone meal? How can you rescue someone of who's sinews are being used to lace trousers made of her own flesh?&quot;<br>
<br>
As he turns to continue his belittlement of Na`Tiel's quest, he his suddenly knocked back by a burst of energy. She would hear no more. Drawing her knife, she begins to walk over to the stunned Varum, intent on opening his throat. The crew begins to close on the fight, some to be witness, some to break it up. Eias grabs her arm to try to restrain her. All pause in wonder as the sound of pleasant laughter rises from the down knight.<br>
<br>
&quot;Well played, evoker,&quot; he shouts as he rises, still laughing. &quot;There is some fight in you after all.&quot;<br>
<br>
Na`Tiel is confused. Although opening his throat still seemed to be a good idea to her, she hesitates, curious as to the intention of her antagonist.<br>
<br>
&quot;The Guardian I know,&quot; he begins, &quot;my knights I know, and the marines I know. You, however, I do not know. I had to find out if you had some fight in you before I would trust going into battle with you. Well played.&quot;<br>
<br>
Lowering her knife, she cannot believe what she is hearing. &quot;Do you think so little of us that you would doubt we would fight for our family. Your little game is insulting!&quot; She goes below, clearly disgusted.<br>
<br>
Joining her below, Eias finds her weeping. &quot;We are kindred spirits, you and I,&quot; she says, sensing him. &quot;Both despised by our societies. The only difference is you are not ridiculed and belittled. Hunted, maybe, but at least respected. I would take your place any day if it meant respect.&quot;<br>
<br>
He joins her at the view - port she has made her favorite. &quot;Respect,&quot; he begins, &quot;is something that can be earned with those who will hear. Granted, Varum went about showing you in the wrong way, but he may be willing to listen and allow you to earn his respect.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;One more exchange like that, thought,&quot; she notes, &quot;will ensure he earns an open throat.&quot;<br>
<br>
The wind and sea grow more favorable, and the fleet is helped along. Come the sunrise, one of the lookouts on the 'Flame' signals the siting of land silhouetted against the sunrise. Navigators on the 'Rage' find landmarks, and turn the fleet southward setting final course for the Outpost. They are a half-day ahead of plans. In a few hours the first signs of their destination appear on the horizon.<br>
<br>
Eias had been to the Outpost before, he notes it is little changed. Ruined well before the Teir`Dal occupied it, it is still mostly that, a ruin. Few buildings are intact and those that are do not offer the same comfort as a nice home in Neriak would. The only real difference this time is the number of people he sees moving about.<br>
<br>
A skeletal herald greets the passengers on the docks as they disembark, relaying some of the ground rules for conduct in the Outpost. Til`Vahn hands a sealed scroll to the herald, making note of a glyph on the seal. The herald gives Til`Vahn some instructions as to who needs to see the scroll. Awaiting Vaxn's scouts, he leads them to a large tent. Handing the scroll to one who appears to be a ranking member of the Brotherhood, he salutes and greets the officer.<br>
<br>
The officer thanks him and states the usual compliments for completing a task and following orders, then dismisses him. Moving to depart, Til`Vahn turns to Eias. &quot;I shall see you on the battlefield, Guardian. I must now join the Brothers in their preparations.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Farewell then, and good fortune to you,&quot; Eias replies.<br>
<br>
The officer informs the rest that they should wait here, an afternoon meal will be brought to them.<br>
<br>
Some time later, after the meal is finished and the table cleared, Varum enters the tent with the officer. Assuring the area is clear of all that need not know he places several parchments on the table. Most are maps showing the route to the mine and it's probable location.<br>
<br>
&quot;This group,&quot; Varum begins, referring to those present in the tent, &quot;leaves before dawn tomorrow to take up position overlooking the mine to pinpoint it. Guardian, this is where you must choose. Will you proceed with these, or do you proceed with the main attack?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I will go with these,&quot; Eias replies. &quot;It is best for Na`Tiel to guide them and my place is with her.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I concur,&quot; Vaxn states, adding his voice of approval.<br>
<br>
&quot;As do I,&quot; Varum notes. Continuing, he explains several points on the map. The mission of the scouts and their guide will be to pinpoint the mine, report its position, and establish numbers of defenders. &quot;Once this is determined, you will dispatch a message to our troops who will be gathering here. Hold position for orders otherwise.&quot; Giving the maps to Vaxn, he dismisses the gathered, &quot;Innoruuk bless our endeavors.&quot; <br>
<br>
Milling about after the meeting, Eias makes note of the shipyard; the 'Rage' had likely been built here. He sees another, similar looking ship almost ready for sea, one named 'Endeavor of the Creator'. The irony of the name and the blessing wished upon them by Varum was not lost.<br>
<br>
Sitting on the beach a bit later, Eias meditates - the sound of the sea clearing his mind. He focuses on the vision of his paths, noting how many converging and diverging paths have fallen away. His choices are becoming more limited, but still the same destination comes closer. Has he chosen wisely, or is he simply being drawn to a false power?<br>
<br>
&quot;I know now why you enjoy the sea,&quot; a small voice comes from beside him.<br>
<br>
&quot;I did not hear you sit down,&quot; he notes, finally noticing Na`Tiel.<br>
<br>
&quot;I did not want to disturb you,&quot; she replies.<br>
<br>
&quot;You didn't.&quot; He is trying to see if he can make out precisely how she fits into this future path, but all he can see is her road diverging from his soon. Many paths part and re-cross his own, but no hers.<br>
<br>
Na`Tiel takes in the sounds of the water and waves, their rhythms filling her being with gentle harmonies. Her mind drifts back to a time when her uncle would play a flute after dinners gathered around a fire, a time of clarity and simple joy she had not felt since.<br>
<br>
Eias rests this night on the beach. In his dream, he focuses on the path he believes to be Na`Tiel's. On tracing it back, he notes a path diverging from hers that does not stray far before approaching again. Conjuring the image of the one who walks that path, he sees a woman who resembles her in every way, but younger and clad similar to a scout of the Ebon Mask. Assuming it to be Na`Vaar, he follows, only to shortly see her kneeling in sorrow near where two paths should intersect hers, both falling short and dissipating to dust. Upon one path, he sees a black ebony mask marking its end, the other a small flame. Awaking suddenly, he looks to see if Na`Tiel is still beside him; she is not.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh, you are already awake,&quot; notes a voice from behind; Vaxn had come to wake him.<br>
<br>
&quot;Na`Vaar is alive,&quot; Eias informs as he rises to join him, &quot;I am fairly certain.&quot;<br>
<br>
A sense of joy settles over Vaxn. He had all but lost hope while waiting, content to undertake the mission out of a vow of vengeance. Coming to the tent where they were serving the morning meal, he informs Na`Tiel of Eias's news.<br>
<br>
A joyous Na`Tiel joins Eias at his table. &quot;How do you know she is alive,&quot; she inquires.<br>
<br>
&quot;I followed her path in a dream,&quot; he explains, &quot;when we get there, at least, she will be alive.&quot; Happily to him, she did not ask about other paths.<br>
<br>
It is still quite dark when they finally make ready to depart. In the distance, Eias notes that Varum has assembled his knights, the Brotherhood, and both the 'Rage's' marines and the local Undead marine platoon, made up of powerful, reanimated Iksar skeletal warriors. Captain Rottgrime, the commander of the undead garrison, is making a speech.<br>
<br>
&quot;Come midday,&quot; he speaks, his raspy, reptilian voice carrying surprisingly well, &quot;we march to bring glory to Innoruuk. We march to punish the ones who took our master's children. We march to show them the power of the Teir`Dal.&quot;<br>
<br>
Varum takes over from there. &quot;What say you, are we ready to march,&quot; he inquires of his army.<br>
<br>
From Varum's knights come the shout, &quot;We are the Dead!&quot;<br>
<br>
Next, the warriors respond, &quot;We are the Brothers!&quot;<br>
<br>
Lastly comes the mixed voice of the undead and living, shouting out, &quot;We are marines!&quot;<br>
