<br>
The blinding snow limited site to only a few feet. Jorn tries to shield his eyes, futilely trying to see his guide. &quot;He has gone to far ahead,&quot; he shouts to the one standing beside him, who still only barely makes out what he says over the howl of the wind.<br>
<br>
&quot;He will come back,&quot; Braxen notes to his companion, more hopeful than certain. Trying to lighten the mood of his Northman friend, he jokes, &quot;This should feel about like home to you, Jorn.'<br>
<br>
&quot;Too cold,&quot; Jorn remarks.<br>
<br>
&quot;I did not think that was possible,&quot; Braxen comments, smiling. Making out a shape coming toward them, he inquires, &quot;Is that Brauen?&quot;<br>
<br>
A lean, light-footed wood elf comes into view from ahead. &quot;I have found us shelter,&quot; Brauen notes, &quot;follow.&quot; Leading on, they come to a cluster of small huts - a remote campsite for Coldain hunters. As they approach, a snow bank near them erupts, hit by a ball of fire.<br>
<br>
Stopping in their tracks, they look around. The storm has lightened a bit, but could intensify again any moment. In the distance, they see flashes of flame silhouetting several large human shapes - too large at that distance to be anything but giants of the Kromrif! Braxen turns to his two companions. No words need to be said; each knows what the other is thinking. They set off in the direction of the battle.<br>
<br>
Coming upon the battle, they note a number of dead Kromrif and an equal number of dead Coldain Dwarves. Still in the fight are three giants, two are beating on an unseen victim and one is battling the elemental fire conjuration of a young Erudite woman; she herself seems to be injured. Several trained wolves seem to be helping the giants.<br>
<br>
Braxen charges the giant engaging the woman's elemental. Two wolves attempt to intercept, one quickly cut down by a swift arrow from Brauen, the other evaded. Jorn gets the attention of one of the giants who is beating on the yet unseen individual by opening the back of its knee with his sword; its cry of pain bringing the third's attention onto Jorn as well, the wolves around them attacking.<br>
<br>
The scouting party has ascended into the mountains near their destination. Na`Tiel begins to recognize landmarks and guides the group to an overlook with a view of the entrance. Making notes on the map, Vaxn directs two of the scouts to close and begin making a count of the guards. The army will not be at it's rendezvous point for another seven hours, so they huddle in and trying to remain unseen using what magic they can.<br>
<br>
The scouts return and give their count. As it stands now, the coming army vastly outnumbers the Iksar at the mine. Na`Tiel seems to recall their being more there when she escaped, a fact that concerns Eias. Looking around, he begins noting the terrain. &quot;They could have dozens more hidden anywhere,&quot; he notes. &quot;We could be walking into an ambush.&quot;<br>
<br>
Vaxn looks around, and concurs. &quot;If that is the case, we must assume we have been spotted, and are vulnerable.&quot; Eias kneels beside him, both checking the map to see where the army would be at that time.<br>
<br>
&quot;Three or four fast runners should try to get a message to the army,&quot; Eias states. &quot;I can enhance their ability to travel over these rocks and canyons. They should run this ridge, then spread out down these paths.&quot;<br>
<br>
Quickly, Vaxn scribes four brief messages in Mask's code. Looking over his scouts, he indexes three. &quot;Svez, you're in charge. You, you, and you with me,&quot; he states, handing each a copy and stowing one in his tunic.<br>
<br>
Eias flashes to his vision of Na`Vaar mourning over an ebony mask. He takes Vaxn by the arm. &quot;Are you sure you should go,&quot; he inquires.<br>
<br>
Confused at first, Vaxn sees the look in Eias's eye. &quot;Yes, I must,&quot; he replies. &quot;My orders are to scout and report, and it is my duty to see it through.&quot; Pausing as if to form a final thought, he gives Eias one last order, &quot;You take care of her.&quot; <br>
<br>
Na`Tiel is keeping her gaze fixed on the mine, a fact of which Eias is thankful, as she did not see his face when Vaxn announced he would bear a message. He calls her over to the four, as she will need to render them unseen once he finishes. Tapping into ancient secrets, he alters their very essence, rendering them ghostlike, pushing them as close to death as he can. They can now drift about like spirits.<br>
<br>
The giant comes to its knees, badly beaten and burned. Its neck is promptly severed by Braxen's heavy blade. Looking about quickly, he notes Jorn and Brauen are both standing, looking around as he is for more foes. Turning to the woman he had moved to protect, he sees she is still breathing, but slowly. Some of the wolves had gotten to her, and a vicious bite near her throat was bleeding badly. Placing his hand on the wound, he calls upon his healing power to seal it and restore some of her strength.<br>
<br>
&quot;Can you walk,&quot; he asks of her.<br>
<br>
&quot;I think so,&quot; she replies.<br>
<br>
Looking about for more survivors, they find none. They discover whom the unseen victim of the two giants was - a human wizard now beaten almost three feet into the snow. A short distance from him lies an ogre with an oddly shaped bruise on it's chest lying next to a giant holding a dead gnome in his hand, the gnome fitting the size of the bruise.<br>
<br>
The snowstorm had let up a little more. Brauen leads them to the huts they had seen earlier. The woman uses some of her magic to quickly light a fire from wood they find stored there, a fortunate thing since the storm again intensifies.<br>
<br>
&quot;What was that fight about,&quot; inquires Jorn.<br>
<br>
Looking about at her rescuers, she notes, with the exception of Brauen, they seem new to the frozen continent. &quot;Are you aware of the conflict here in the Eastern Waste?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Vaguely,&quot; notes Braxen. &quot;I know about the Coldain - Kromrif war.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You have just walked into the middle of it,&quot; she states. &quot;I was supporting some skirmishers. The Coldain main line is about a mile and a half northwest.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;They should have heard the fight then,&quot; Braxen notes.<br>
<br>
&quot;Even if they did,&quot; Brauen interrupts, &quot;a mile and a half out here may as well be forever in these storms.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;We should rest here as well as we can,&quot; the woman notes, &quot;these huts are not safe.&quot;<br>
<br>
Waiting out the storm, they all take note of the sound of the wind. It has changed to a deeper, almost mournful demeanor with a touch of hate thrown in. As the storm begins to wind down, they note the new tone does not fade, but grows stronger.<br>
<br>
Suddenly, Brauen knocks an arrow and fires it out the door. The high pitched yap of a dire wolf confirms the arrow found it's target. Wounded, the wolf tries to flee, but a second arrow finishes it.<br>
<br>
&quot;We must go now,&quot; the woman insists. &quot;The Kromrif are close.&quot;<br>
<br>
The sky is clearing; the only falling snow is light and dry. Coming over a hill near the huts, Braxen can look across a valley to see the site of the recent fight. Standing over the dead, a giant eyes the fallen. It leans back, howling a deep dirge that sounds like a cold, icy wind. From over distant hills, other Kromrif appear, closing on the position of the howling comrade.<br>
<br>
Braxen sees the Coldain's lines to the northwest; several mounds of snow have been erected as a wall around a camp. It seems prudent to him to reach that camp, as the group has now been spotted by a pack of the Kromrif's wolves.<br>
<br>
Vaxn and his scouts glide effortlessly over the rocks and canyons. Their feet rarely come close to the ground. &quot;I could get use to this,&quot; he thinks to himself. The army was at least twenty miles away when they set out, and they had covered most of that distance in a very short time.<br>
<br>
They begin to pass down a canyon that would lead them to the open area where they would fan out and try to locate the army. Midway through, the scout at the end of their line shouts, &quot;Ambush!&quot;<br>
<br>
Turning about, they see the second to last become engulfed by magical energy that forms a bond of force fixing him in place, the same has happened to the last. An Iksar clad in banded scale armor leaps from the rock above and behind them. It begins to cast its rooting magic again, but is interrupted by a barrage of throwing blades. Vaxn and the one still free close with it as it falls back.<br>
<br>
The Iksar has pulled them past their companions. A shout comes from one; two warriors who leaped down from the rocks above have struck him from behind. Struggling against his magical bonds, he manages to get his sword free, but is badly wounded. His bound companion throws a few blades into one, who turns on him.<br>
<br>
Vaxn orders the one with him to help the others. &quot;I'll keep this one busy,&quot; he states. Drawing two fighting knives from his belt, he continues to close. Noting it is no longer two against one, the Iksar begins to stand its ground.<br>
<br>
Content that their first victim is down, the two warriors engage the two scouts. The bound one manages to hold his own while still fighting the magic. The one still free manages to get inside the reach of his foe, opening up some sizeable wounds with his knives.<br>
<br>
The two warriors have underestimated the resilience of a Teir`Dal. Freeing himself from the magical bonds, the wounded scout recovers his dropped sword. He manages to find a suitable place to put his blade along the back of the Iksar on his still bound comrade. Shrieking in pain, the warrior brings its own sword down upon the head of the impetuous rogue who has just impaled him, only to expose his back to the rogue's comrade, who does the same. The warrior falls to its knees, where one last blow to the head sends it slumping lifelessly to the ground beside the now lifeless scout.<br>
<br>
Vaxn charges his foe. The Iksar evades with magical nimbleness. Neither has been able to harm the other yet, but the Iksar commands still more powers. Allowing Vaxn to charge and miss again, he evokes spirit energies that slam into his foe, sending him reeling in pain. Recovering, Vaxn charges again, more carefully this time, feigning one direction and coming back on the Iksar when he dodges, one knife finding its mark, creating a serious wound.<br>
<br>
Growing tired of this dance; the Iksar becomes more aggressive. After hitting his foe with another spirit strike, it lunges with its spear as Vaxn turns. The spear catches him in the chest, penetrating deep. Pinning its foe to the ground, it twists the spear, the sound of metal grinding on stone apparent from beneath Vaxn.<br>
<br>
Although writhing in agony, Vaxn remained lucid. Slamming his foot into the knee of his attacker, he knocks a leg from under it. Now with it in arm's reach, he slashes at the Iksar's throat, catching a piece of its neck. Renewing its grip on the spear and its footing, it grinds a bit more, blinding Vaxn in pain. Through the agony, he hears a soft impact on the ground next to him. Opening his eyes, he sees the two surviving members of his team standing over him, the Iksar lying at his side with two swords in its back.<br>
<br>
Attempting to evade the pack of dire wolves pursuing them, Braxen and his group make for what appears to be the dwarven camp. Brauen does his best to slow the pack, using his speed and skill as a ranger to confuse and slow the animals. The Kromrif are closing, however.<br>
<br>
Brauen catches up to Braxen; Jorn and the woman are ahead of them. He sends an arrow into a wolf pursuing him, but the animal does not slow. Before he can notch another, several more arrows strike it, stopping it dead. The Coldain have spread out, and Braxen and Brauen are passing through a line of hidden crossbow - armed dwarves. They all reach the dwarf camp safely. Looking back, they see Kromrif coming over a ridge behind them cut down one by one as the concealed dwarves take their shots.<br>
<br>
Braxen is introduced to the dwarven commander. &quot;We thank you Outlander,&quot; he says in greeting, &quot;and ask if you will stand with us?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I will,&quot; he replies. Looking around, he sees around three dozen warriors. Knowing there are more, he asks how many warriors there are.<br>
<br>
&quot;Enough,&quot; the commander states confidently. Braxen does note a hint of uneasiness in the commander's voice.<br>
<br>
The Kromrif end their rush and fall back behind the ridge. Quiet settles over the area, but the occasional heavy footfalls of the giants can be heard. Climbing to a high spot, the commander sees what the giants are waiting for; another bad storm is heading their way, and night is about to fall. On more distant hills, the occasional band of giants is seen coming toward the ridge where the others wait. When they come, they will come in force.<br>
<br>
Vaxn is quivering from the pain. Knowing withdrawing the spear fully would likely kill him, they have managed to break off the shaft - the shock causing him to drop his blades. The two discuss how they should proceed, but Vaxn had already made up his mind.<br>
<br>
&quot;You two get the message to the army,&quot; he orders, fighting the pain to remain focused, &quot;If there is time, come back for me, but do not make special effort.&quot;<br>
<br>
Saying a quick parting word, they depart with haste. They get some distance away when he hears the Iksar beside him begin to stir. Standing, it sees him, a bloody mess with a spear in his chest, then sees the two departing. Removing the swords from its back and grabbing its shield, it seems to be preparing to give chase. Vaxn looks around for a weapon, but there is only one handy.<br>
<br>
Speaking a quiet prayer to Innoruuk, he closes his eyes to brace for a shock of pain. Placing his hands firmly on the remaining shaft of the spear, he pulls it from his chest, successfully resisting the urge to cry out. Standing slowly, he sees the Iksar begin to cast some sort of magic. With his last bit of strength, he hurls the spear point, implanting it into the back of the Iksar's head, the crunching of bone confirming a firm hit, followed by the cold thump of dead flesh.<br>
<br>
Each of his heartbeats now inched him closer to the end, his heart now fully open. He thanks Innoruuk for his last bit of strength, but his final thought is of Na`Vaar. He slumps to his knees, the strength leaving him. &quot;I love you, cousin,&quot; is the last phrase to leave his lips as his final bit of life departs.<br>
<br>
An icy chill comes over Eias. It had happened! The vision of the ebony mask, now bloodstained, returns and disturbs his meditation. Na`Tiel and the scouts are startled by his sudden reaction to something unseen. Focusing, he notes, &quot;be ready, we may have to make a stand here.&quot; Turning inward as they make preparations, he focuses on the image of the bloody mask, probing it for any hidden meaning.<br>
<br>
Reaching the army, the two scouts find Varum. He reads the message, &quot;Ambush likely. Position possibly compromised. Plan likely anticipated.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Captain,&quot; he calls out to Rottgrime, &quot;take your marines and reinforce the scouts. Hurry!&quot;<br>
<br>
The storm hits. The swirling snow blinds almost everyone and nightfall makes it worse. Noise from the wind makes verbal communications almost impossible. If the Kromrif are coming, it will be soon. Braxen finds Jorn and Brauen; he will stand by them as they fight.<br>
<br>
The giants have let their dogs loose upon the dwarves. The sounds of injured canines can faintly be heard on the wind. Another sound begins to rise, the howl of the giants. It is clearly audible over the wind. Braxen estimates many dozens, perhaps hundreds of giants howling at once from over the ridge. It suddenly stops, and everyone within site of Braxen suddenly becomes very alert.<br>
<br>
The sound of battle rises from ahead of the lines; the Kromrif have come over the ledge. Hidden warriors rise up out of the snow and engage the giants as they come near. The sound of bowstrings soon begins as the crossbowmen add their weight to the fight.<br>
<br>
Any moment now, Braxen expects giants to come into view ahead of him. His eyes strain to see through the blowing snow. The sound of battle, however, grows fainter. A runner comes up to the commander and shouts something in his ear; the giants are falling back.<br>
<br>
Had the lines held? From the sounds of the howling, they had all expected to see hundreds of giants. Had Brell brought them such good fortune? The answer was coming up from behind!<br>
<br>
The giants had used the sound of the storm and the distraction of the battle to move the bulk of their force behind the dwarves and now that force was charging into the camp with little hindrance! The small force of dwarves that had stayed to cover the camp was now being overrun with ease. Dwarves began to leave their hiding places and fall back into the camp. In the confusion, Braxen becomes separated from his companions, fighting for his life in the midst of this blinding snowstorm.<br>
<br>
The scouts have returned to the site of the ambush. They see the spearpoint in the head of the Iksar. He had given his life for them. Removing his bloodstained ebon mask, they take it with them.<br>
<br>
Starting from the vision of the mask, Eias focuses. Remembering the ancient secrets he had studied, he began reciting the rhymes of the prophets. One gives him the key, &quot;The dead in their slumber are ungiving. To answer your vision, look to the living.&quot; He begins tracing back the path of the mask and sees the Iksar whom he battled. This added to the dread, he knows now they are facing forces lead by the Scaled Mystics, the shaman of Calibis. This battle will be bloody. Noting the path of that Iksar ending, he traced it back. It intersected many other paths, mainly the ones the Mystics have enslaved to work this mine; the climate was too cold and dry for their usual froglok slaves, so alternatives had to be explored. From these intersections, he focuses on the paths of other shaman who seemed involved in the mine. Most begin to lead quite close, but one begins to approach quickly, heading right for the path that ends in the small flame.<br>
<br>
Coming to his feet immediately, he grabs small chips of bone from a small pouch on his belt. Holding them tightly, he begins to focus energy into them. Startled by this, the scouts become nervous. The snap of a bowstring gets their attention; an Iksar warrior stands upon a rock above them. Its arrow glances harmlessly off an energy field surrounding Eias.<br>
<br>
The channeling of energy complete, Eias tosses the bones into the air, which form a skeletal protector. The warrior on the rock ducks back down upon seeing that. &quot;They are here,&quot; Eias notes, &quot;and they are coming now!&quot; Focusing inward, his flesh peals away from his bone, retreating inward to be channeled into power, a howl rising from his soul that is heard for miles around, echoing off the rocks. &quot;Stay with me,&quot; he tells Na`Tiel, his voice now hollow and fearsome.<br>
<br>
Moonlight finally breaks through the clouds as the storm dissipates. The snow is bright red, saturated with the blood of over one hundred dwarves and giants. The battle still rages, the Kromrif appear to be winning. This day does not go well for the Coldain.<br>
<br>
The commander finds Braxen somehow. Handing him a sealed letter, he requests that he take it to the Dian immediately. Looking about to find Jorn, he sees him. Lying amongst a pile of dwarves, the lifeless eyes of Jorn and Brauen stare into the sky. Muttering a prayer requesting forgiveness from his fallen friends, he sets out westward toward the pass to the valley of the Great Divide, it lay within view ahead of him. One of the Kromrif spots Braxen as he leaves the fight. Reaching down, it grabs the closest dwarf and hurls it at him.<br>
<br>
He has just made it over the last barrier mound the dwarves erected. Focusing on the valley ahead, he is suddenly struck from behind with incredible force, driving him forward into a snowdrift. Slowly he rises to his feet, back bruised severely. Turning to see what struck him, he spots a dwarven woman lying in the snow. Her small size suddenly reminds Braxen of a small child and he immediately comes to her side. Her neck is slightly skewed; likely indicating it is broken.<br>
<br>
&quot;Are you ok,&quot; he asks, as if to a little girl.<br>
<br>
Her eyes open slightly. &quot;Run, you fool,&quot; she says weakly, noting the letter in his cloak pocket. &quot;There's nothing you can do for me. Run!&quot;<br>
<br>
Looking up, he quickly comes to his senses. The Kromrif who hurled the little one has grabbed a pair of its comrades, all three setting out in pursuit of Braxen.<br>
<br>
&quot;Run, now,&quot; she says, trying to shout.<br>
<br>
He finally does just that. He heads into the valley with three Kromrif soldiers in hot pursuit. The young dwarf is later found inside one of the giant's footprints. A hail of arrows from behind cuts down two, but one still remains. Braxen manages to use his powers to stun it, but only briefly enough to make it through the valley.<br>
<br>
The scouts have managed to maneuver the battle into a small box canyon, narrowing their front to a manageable size. Eias is keeping the number of Iksar's on the line low by using his power of fear to make them flee. A shaman stands back from its warriors, enhancing them and healing them as needed. Eias has been siphoning away the life force of the Iksar warriors and using it as vital healing energy, keeping alive the scouts that are holding the line.<br>
<br>
A dilemma confronts Eias. The shaman leading the warriors will eventually wear down, but how long will that take? As long as it keeps healing the warriors, this fight will go on for a while. Sending his skeletal companion after the shaman will leave Eias and Na'Tiel vulnerable, as the skeleton is picking off Iksar that break through the lines. If he focuses his magic on the Iksar, the scouts will be cut down quickly. The dilemma is made more pressing by the appearance of another column of Iksar warriors and their shaman captain.<br>
<br>
The second shaman decides to up the price, it attacks Eias directly, letting the first shaman continue as healer. Focusing, it lets loose a spirit strike, impacting hard on Eias still skeletal frame. The companion charges, and is intercepted by a force of warriors.<br>
<br>
&quot;This is bad,&quot; Eias thinks to himself. Turning to Na`Tiel, he tells her, &quot;if that line falls, I want you to port out of here like you did before. I will hold them as long as I can.&quot; She agrees.<br>
<br>
The shaman again focuses for a spirit strike. A swift blow to the back of the head interrupts its casting. The marines have arrived! Captain Rottgrime engages the shaman, quickly cutting it down. Spreading out, the marines quickly disperse the Iksar.<br>
<br>
Eias relaxes, allowing his flesh to return. Severely weakened, his skin is pale. Most of the scouts have small bits of his life force in them; his ability to heal exacts a severe price from him, made even more severe by his channeling of his own life force to reinforce his magic. He will recover though.<br>
<br>
Braxen stumbles toward a small tower by a stream. He is exhausted and beaten and there are still Kromrif pursuing him. He only knew the general path to Thurgadin, but his guide is now dead. As he comes to the tower, two dwarves approach. Here he hoped was help.<br>
<br>
He stumbles and lands on his knees. The sound of heavy footsteps can be heard coming from behind him. One of the dwarves signals some others upstream a ways, and a band of nearly a dozen warriors and crossbowman rush over, taking up a line. Braxen stumbles through, handing the note to the guard. &quot;I must get this to the Dain,&quot; he states.<br>
<br>
Examining the letter, the guard confirms its legitimacy. &quot;As you shall,&quot; he replies.<br>
<br>
Eias returns to the overlook where they kept watch on the mine. Teir`Dal marines have surrounded the entrance and knights from the Dead have entered. One by one freed slaves emerge, some seeing the sun for the first time in a near eternity. A few spot Eias on the ledge and wave with recognition, his former companions in battle were freed.<br>
<br>
Stepping away from the ledge, he sees Na`Tiel warmly embracing someone. The vision had been correct, Na`Vaar is alive. The scouts bring Vaxn's mask to the sisters, who recognize it. Eias comes over to them as they explain how he died, the sisters weeping softly at the news.<br>
<br>
&quot;Guardian,&quot; shouts a familiar voice from the distance. Til`Vahn has joined them on the ledge followed closely by Varum. Eias greets the dragoon warmly. &quot;We have avenged them,&quot; he notes, happily thanking Eias for the help.<br>
<br>
&quot;My task here is complete then,&quot; Eias states. &quot;There is one last thing, though.&quot; Removing the Rune of the Guardian, he asks Na`Tiel who should take it now.<br>
<br>
Varum speaks up on that note. &quot;You do not have to return it,&quot; he states. &quot;Once given, it can be permanent. There are privileges given to Guardians. For that matter, she was practically yours in ways you were probably not told about. Given away, even after the task is done, transfers no privileges.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;It would have not mattered,&quot; Eias replies. &quot;I have other issues that would complicate this if I kept it. Where I go next I cannot take her.&quot; Again, he asks Na`Tiel who to give the rune to.<br>
<br>
&quot;I cannot talk you into keeping it,&quot; she asks. Upon him saying no, she requests it be given to Til`Vahn.<br>
<br>
Handing it to her, he tells her to place it on his neck. Ranting through an abbreviated and humorous version of the speech he was given when he received it, he tells him to return it to it's keeper in Neriak.<br>
<br>
As he prepares to leave, Na`Tiel takes him in a farewell embrace. &quot;Perhaps,&quot; she whispers so only he can hear, &quot;when you come back to Neriak, I can tell you about the privileges you still have.&quot;<br>
<br>
Smiling softly as she releases the embrace, he steps away. With a gentle wave to all, he fades from their sight.<br>
<br>
Healers attend to Braxen as he is prepared to be taken to the Dain. One of the healers questions him about the massive bruise on his back. &quot;What hit you,&quot; he asks.<br>
<br>
&quot;Apologies,&quot; he replies, dark saddened undertones to his voice, &quot;I did not ask her name.&quot;<br>
<br>
Slightly confused, the healer can see Braxen wishes not to discuss it, and resumes his work. Cleaned up to Coldain standards, he is briefed on the proper way to address the Dain. He is then escorted to the Dain's castle, the mighty Icewell Keep. A great crowd has gathered in the main hall for the daily audience of the beloved ruler of the Coldain.<br>
<br>
In the great hall, much pomp and ceremony conclude with the announcement of the arrival of Dain Frostreaver IV. After some usual addresses by the Chancellor and other advisors, Braxen is presented, and the letter given. The Dain's spirits sink slightly as he reads it. &quot;It is a dark day all,&quot; laments the Dain, &quot;our forces in the Eastern Waste have been overrun.&quot; The mood of the assembly darkens.<br>
<br>
&quot;Perhaps,&quot; Braxen states, &quot;I can humbly offer some insights as to why.&quot;<br>
<br>
Curious, the Dane asks Braxen to continue.<br>
<br>
Drawing himself to his full height, he begins by explaining that his trip to Velious was done with the purpose of seeing the Dain, and how fortune had smiled upon him, circumstances bringing him right where he intended to be.<br>
<br>
&quot;I have come to warn you about a culture of liars and evil - doers,&quot; he continues. &quot;Recently, a friend of mine was murdered by one of them. My people refer to them as the Heretics. They spread fear wherever they go. They conjure up the undead and drain the life out of all they touch.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;How is it that this could have caused our defeat today,&quot; interrupts the Dain, not wanting a long speech by Braxen to upstage him.<br>
<br>
&quot;Because you people have allied yourself with one of them, the murder of my friend,&quot; he replies. &quot;Eias Rham is an evil murderer, yet I hear that some of your people consider him a close ally.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;We seek the aid of many people,&quot; notes the Dain. &quot;Brell gives us no restrictions on who to trust and who to not trust. They are all given fair chance to prove themselves. Eias did just that.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Allying yourselves with this Heretic,&quot; he warns, &quot;may in the long run turn the other gods against Brell. Maybe this is the first sign of such a thing.&quot;<br>
<br>
Pondering a moment, the Dain responds, &quot;your heart may be in the right place on this one, Outlander. We will take this under advisement.&quot; Dismissing Braxen, the Dain departs to his chambers.<br>
<br>
Turning to the Dain's Chancellor, Braxen inquires, &quot;I have comrades lying in the Waste. Would it be possible for me to have a guide show me to where they fell.&quot;<br>
<br>
The Chancellor ponders a moment. &quot;Likely,&quot; he notes, &quot;the bodies are buried in deep snow by now or carried off by wolves. We have no soldiers to spare for such a task, nor would it be likely possible to find them easily anyway.&quot; He begins to walk away, then stops, as if a point of irony suddenly occurs to him. &quot;It sounds,&quot; he continues, &quot;like you need the services of a Necromancer.&quot; Laughing lightly to himself, he retires to his chambers.<br>
<br>
Strolling out of Icewell back into the city, he passes through the connecting tunnel. A voice from nowhere asks, &quot;Do you have any message I should relay to Palatos, Braxen?&quot; Stopping cold, he looks around slowly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, I do,&quot; he replies, &quot;but I wish to see the face of the messenger first.&quot;<br>
<br>
A black cloaked Erudite steps out from a shadow. Throwing back the cloak, he reveals the crystalline green robe beneath. Braxen could hardly believe his eyes. The object of his long chase was now standing before him! &quot;Eias,&quot; he shouts from between clenched teeth, &quot;you have a lot of nerve pulling this.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I wish to end this,&quot; Eias announces, &quot;I do not want to have to kill you to do it though. Give me a message to give to Palatos that will tell him to stand down.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;What makes you think Palatos is involved,&quot; Braxen inquires, probing more than anything.<br>
<br>
Noting the question as leading, he evades. &quot;It matters not how I know,&quot; rebuffs Eias, &quot;only that without a word from you now, he may not get a chance to carry out your orders.&quot;<br>
<br>
Circling each other like two boxers ready to pounce, they size each other up. Neither had actually met the other before, so they were both curious as to what made the other what they are.<br>
<br>
&quot;Give me the word, Braxen,&quot; Eias continued, &quot;we end this now and no one has to die.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Wrong,&quot; shouted Braxen, &quot;you killed my friend. You murdered an agent of the Law. You murdered a Knight of Truth.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;He took the law into his own hands,&quot; Eias replies, &quot;and in his own fine method I avenged the one he killed. I did nothing different than he.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You had no right,&quot; Braxen screamed.<br>
<br>
&quot;You who brand us outlaw upon birth speak of rights,&quot; Eias inquires. &quot;Do not speak of rights when the only rights you yourself respect are those taken by force.&quot;<br>
<br>
Braxen has had enough. &quot;Eias Rham, I condemn you to death! You who spread lies and cause fear. You preach heresy, you live heresy, and you murder those that bring justice!&quot; He draws his sword and charges Eias, who fades away as the blade passes through where he stood.<br>
<br>
Looking about, he realizes Eias is gone. Screaming out of frustration, he shouts, &quot;I shall hunt you down, Heretic! I promise this! Edwin shall be avenged!&quot; The weight of recent events suddenly hits him. Edwin, Jorn, Brauen, the woman in the waste and the young dwarf, neither of whom he has a name for; they are all dead. He should have been able to save them all, but they now sit on his soul like black failures. &quot;I shall avenge them all,&quot; he vows.<br>
<br>
Stacks of wood line the seashore, each holding the body of a fallen Teir`Dal. One by one a torch is passed down the line, and each fire is lit. Na`Tiel and Na`Vaar, wearing her own ebon mask in tribute, stand over the body of their fallen cousin. The torch reaches their pile and is handed to Na`Vaar.<br>
<br>
Turning to her sister, she holds the torch out to her. Na`Tiel reaches into the flame, taking some of it and allowing it to envelope her hand. Some at first think she is on fire, but quickly realize she is controlling the flame. Stretching forth her hand, the fire leaps onto the wood, quickly spreading through the pyre.<br>
<br>
The speed of the conflagration gets the attention of everyone on the beach. Astonished that she would change the tradition of the burning so flagrantly, they quickly accept it, knowing she did it to honor her fallen cousin. Na`Vaar passes the torch down the line.<br>
<br>
All the fires are lit. Each at the procession now holds a chalice of sacred wine. In unison, they drink a toast to vengeance.<br>
<br>
Sariah stands on a balcony overlooking the fountain walkway leading to the Temple of Marr. News that Palatos Kynarn's body had been found outside the walls disturbed her. She knew questions would now be raised that she did not wish answered. Braxen still had friends among the knights, and she now feared for her life and the life of her sister. Would they find out she passed information to Eias about Braxen's plan and Palatos's orders?<br>
<br>
&quot;Trouble,&quot; inquires a voice from behind. One of Sariah's old teachers, Malien, joins her. &quot;You look as if the weight of all of Norrath bears down upon you.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You heard of the murder,&quot; she asks of Malien.<br>
<br>
&quot;Which one,&quot; Malien replies, blunt humor clearly in the response. &quot;This is Freeport, and in Lucan's zone murder is commonplace. I know which one you mean, though, Palatos Kynarn. He was trouble, and associating himself with Braxen only signed his death warrant. He should have known Eias, or for that matter the Plaguebringers, would come after him eventually.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You knew of his plot with Braxen,&quot; Sariah inquires, clearly shocked.<br>
<br>
&quot;We all knew,&quot; Malien notes, &quot;there was only one of us, though, who could do anything about it.&quot;<br>
<br>
Relieved, Sariah finally allows herself to smile. Turning to move back into the temple, they note a man standing in the doorway who was not there a moment earlier. Recognizing him, Sariah takes Eias in an embrace.<br>
<br>
&quot;Showing yourself here takes courage,&quot; Malien notes.<br>
<br>
&quot;I had to come,&quot; he replies, &quot;I had to make sure she knew. I already saw Leirna and told her.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;She has nothing to fear here, Eias,&quot; the old teacher states. &quot;Although she may not be popular with the Knights of Truth at the moment, she has not dishonored herself, quite the contrary. A few of us in the order of Erollisi enjoy reminding our brother order that truth is subjective, and that simply because they do not like a particular version does not make it any less true. She, and her sister, will be safe, you have my word on that.&quot;<br>
<br>
Back on the hill in the western Commonlands where this adventure began, Eias sits and ponders how such a chance encounter changed so much, though the path ahead was just as hazardous as before and just as long. While the energy of the moment still allowed, he had viewed the paths of many close friends, noting with interest how Leirna's was cut short by Palatos's path, a situation he had corrected. Na`Tiel and Na`Vaar now enjoyed a long life ahead of them, their paths never straying far from one another. The calmness of the moments now relegating his vision of the paths to a fleeting dream, he focuses again on choices ahead.<br>
